You don't have to reload the whole html page in order to change the image, in fact you can pre-cache the images if you don't, leading to a smoother slideshow. Here's an example.Note: Change the listOfImageUrls which I'm lazy and auto-generate to your own array of urls to different images.slideshow.html<!DOCTYPE html><html lang=en><head>  <meta charset=UTF-8>  <meta http-equiv=X-UA-Compatible content=IE=edge>  <meta name=viewport content=width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0>  <title>Slideshow</title>  <link rel=stylesheet href=slideshow.css></head><body>  <script src=slideshow.js></script></body></html>slideshow.cssbody {  background-color: black;  background-size: cover;  background-attachment: fixed;}slidehow.js// How many seconds before shifting imageconst secondsBetweenSlides = 5;// An array of image urls - just generating from unsplash for nowconst listOfImageUrls = [...new Array(15)].map(() =>  `https://source.unsplash.com/random/?food&nocache=${Math.random()}`);// Sleep for a number of msconst sleep = ms => new Promise(res => setTimeout(res, ms));// Run the showconst slideShow = async () => {  while (true) {    let imageToShow = listOfImageUrls.shift();    listOfImageUrls.push(imageToShow)    document.body.style.backgroundImage = `url(${imageToShow})`;    await sleep(secondsBetweenSlides * 1000);  }}slideShow();
